 to define clearly what institutional change is; failure to specify the mechanisms responsible for institutional change; and failure to explain adequately how "ideas" other than self-interests affect institutional change. To demonstrate the utility of his tools for resolving the problems of institutional analysis, Campbell applies them to the phenomenon of globalization. In doing so, he not only corrects serious misunderstandings about globalization, but also develops a new theory of institutional change. This book advances the new institutional analysis by showing how the different paradigms can benefit from constructive dialogue and cross-fertilization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aGlobalization. 0aOrganizational change. 0aSocial institutions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aEastern Europe.  aEuropean Union.  aKeynesianism.  aNetherlands.  aanti-terrorist programs.  aart museums.  abackground assumptions.  abricolage.  acausal mechanisms.  acognitive ideas.  acurrency policy.  ademocratization.  aderegulation.  aelectoral institutions.  afeedback mechanisms.  aforeground ideas.  ahealth care systems.  aideas.  aidentities.  ainteraction patterns.  alegal systems.  amethodological individualism.  amonetarism.  aownership rights.  aportfolio investment.  aproperty rights.  aquantitative analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691216348zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691216348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691216348.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c